					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornetcorset" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2670686); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2670686&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182106" alt="hornetcorset" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2670686)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/hornetcorset" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2670686); return false;" >hornetcorset</a></span> <span class="odate time_1487717963 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Feb 2017 22:59</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2752258">
									

<p>I'd like to point out that your main issue here is your inclusion of a second BEE. Hexadecimal color codes are defined as 0xRRGGBB, where RR is the amount of red, GG is the amount of green, and BB is the amount of blue. This works by using the additive color wheel, in which yellow is the combination of red and green. C0, beeing similar to BE, is three-fourths of the way to maximum. E0 is actually fifteen-sixteenths of the way, making the yellow produced by the code 0xBEE000 a slightly-darker, somewhat-greenish yellow, but yellow nonetheless. Technically, the most yellow a yellow can bee is 0xFFFF00.</p>

							</div>

								
					
